From a plain textarea to a full-stack OWASP-hardened app with Google Sign-In, rich text editing, full-text search, and auto-save.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Screenshot of the notes dashboardI recently built a full-stack notes application that I’m genuinely proud of. Not because it does something novel — notes apps are everywhere — but because of how it’s built. Every decision was deliberate: the database schema, the security layer, the way content is stored, how files are handled, even how the app behaves when the server is asleep. This article covers everything. The tech choices, the tricky problems, the bugs I caught before they shipped, and the engineering decisions I’d defend in an interview. I’ll share real code throughout.
Live demo: notes-frontend-j8qo.onrender.com
GitHub: github.com/Rememberful/secured-messaging.
The Stack:
Part 1: Starting with a Solid Foundation
The Database Schema Before writing a single route, I designed the schema. Every engineering decision flows from here
-- Users — supports both email/password and Google Sign-In
CREATE TABLE users (
id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
email TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,
name TEXT,
password_hash TEXT, -- NULL for Google-only accounts
google_id TEXT UNIQUE, -- NULL for password-only accounts
created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);-- Notes — content stored as Tiptap JSON
CREATE TABLE notes (
id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
user_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
title TEXT NOT NULL,
content TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT '',
-- Generated column: Postgres maintains this automatically on every INSERT/UPDATE
-- Weight A = title (ranks higher), Weight B = content
search_vector tsvector GENERATED ALWAYS AS (
setweight(to_tsvector('english', coalesce(title, '')), 'A') ||
setweight(to_tsvector('english', coalesce(content, '')), 'B')
) STORED,
created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
updated_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);
-- GIN index makes full-text search fast at scale
CREATE INDEX idx_notes_search_vector ON notes USING GIN (search_vector);
-- Tags: many-to-many, scoped per user
CREATE TABLE tags (
id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
user_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
name TEXT NOT NULL,
UNIQUE (user_id, name)
);
CREATE TABLE note_tags (
note_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES notes(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
tag_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES tags(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
PRIMARY KEY (note_id, tag_id)
);
-- Media: images stored as bytea
CREATE TABLE media (
id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
note_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES notes(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
user_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
filename TEXT NOT NULL,
mime_type TEXT NOT NULL,
size_bytes INTEGER NOT NULL CHECK (size_bytes <= 2097152), -- 2MB DB-level hard cap
data BYTEA NOT NULL,
created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);
-- Password reset tokens: hashed, single-use, expiring
CREATE TABLE password_reset_tokens (
id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
user_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
token_hash TEXT NOT NULL, -- SHA-256 hash of the raw token
expires_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL,
used_at TIMESTAMPTZ, -- NULL until redeemed
created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);
Three design decisions worth calling out:

• search_vector is a generated column. This is the most interesting one. Instead of maintaining the search index in application code (which is a bug waiting to happen — someone will forget to update it on PUT ), I let Postgres do it automatically. Every INSERT and UPDATE regenerates the tsvector from title and content , weighted so title matches rank higher. A GIN index makes it fast.

• Tags are many-to-many with a proper join table — not a TEXT[] array column or a comma-separated string. Both of those are shortcuts that make filtering and counting painful later. A join table with cascade deletes is the right answer and it’s not significantly more complex.

• password_hash and google_id are both nullable. A user who signed up via Google has no password_hash . A user who signed up with email/password has no google_id . If the same email signs in via Google later, we link them by setting google_id on the existing row.
Part 2: Auth — Done Right
Email/Password with bcrypt
// backend/src/routes/auth.jsrouter.post('/signup', signupLimiter, validateBody(signupSchema), async (req, res) => {
const { email, password, name } = req.body;
// email is already trimmed + lowercased by the zod schema
const existing = await pool.query('SELECT id FROM users WHERE email = $1', [email]);
if (existing.rows.length > 0) {
return res.status(409).json({ error: 'An account with that email already exists' });
}
// Cost factor 12 — meaningfully more brute-force resistant than the default 10
const passwordHash = await bcrypt.hash(password, 12);
const result = await pool.query(
'INSERT INTO users (email, name, password_hash) VALUES ($1, $2, $3) RETURNING *',
[email, name || null, passwordHash]
);
const token = issueToken(result.rows[0]);
res.status(201).json({ token, user: publicUser(result.rows[0]) });
});
The JWT carries issuer and audience claims, verified on every request:
function issueToken(user) {
return jwt.sign({ sub: user.id, email: user.email }, process.env.JWT_SECRET, {
expiresIn: '7d',
issuer: 'notes-app',
audience: 'notes-app-client',
});
}Why does this matter? If the same `JWT_SECRET` were ever reused across services, a token signed for Service A couldn’t be used against Service B because the `audience` claim wouldn’t match. Defense in depth.
Google Sign-In — Server-Side Verification
This is the part most tutorials get wrong. They decode the JWT the browser sends from Google and trust it. Never do this. The correct flow:

• Browser shows Google’s button (via the GSI SDK)

• User clicks — Google returns a signed credential token to the browser

• Browser sends that raw token to your backend

• Your backend verifies it against Google’s servers
router.post('/google', authAttemptLimiter, validateBody(googleAuthSchema), async (req, res) => {
const { credential } = req.body; const ticket = await googleClient.verifyIdToken({
idToken: credential,
audience: process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID, // Rejects tokens for other apps
});
const payload = ticket.getPayload();
const { sub: googleId, email: rawEmail, name, email_verified } = payload;
// Normalize email — Google can return mixed case
const email = rawEmail.trim().toLowerCase();
if (!email_verified) {
return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Google account email is not verified' });
}
// Find existing user or create new one
let result = await pool.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE google_id = $1', [googleId]);
let user = result.rows[0];
if (!user) {
// Link to existing email/password account if emails match
const existingResult = await pool.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1', [email]);
if (existingResult.rows[0]) {
await pool.query('UPDATE users SET google_id = $1 WHERE id = $2', [googleId, existingResult.rows[0].id]);
user = { ...existingResult.rows[0], google_id: googleId };
} else {
const insertResult = await pool.query(
'INSERT INTO users (email, name, google_id) VALUES ($1, $2, $3) RETURNING *',
[email, name || null, googleId]
);
user = insertResult.rows[0];
}
}
res.json({ token: issueToken(user), user: publicUser(user) });
});
