The login page showing both the email/password form and the “Continue with Google” buttonPart 3: OWASP Top 10 — Actually Implementing It
Most projects say “we follow OWASP.” Let me show you what that actually looks like in code.
Rate Limiting (API4 — Unrestricted Resource Consumption)
// backend/src/middleware/rateLimiters.jsexport const authAttemptLimiter = rateLimit({
windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
max: 10, // 10 attempts per IP
message: { error: 'Too many attempts. Please try again in a few minutes.' },
});
export const signupLimiter = rateLimit({
windowMs: 60 * 60 * 1000, // 1 hour
max: 10,
message: { error: 'Too many accounts created from this location.' },
});
I verified this actually works — hitting /api/auth/login 12 times in a row, the first 10 got 401 (wrong credentials), attempts 11 and 12 correctly got 429 . The app also needs app.set(‘trust proxy’, 1) — without it, all traffic behind Render’s load balancer looks like it comes from the same IP, making rate limiting useless.
Input Validation + Mass Assignment Protection (API8, A03)
// backend/src/validation/schemas.jsexport const noteCreateSchema = z.object({
title: z.string().trim().min(1, 'Title is required').max(200),
content: z.string().max(50000).optional().default(''),
tags: z.array(z.string().trim().max(40)).max(20).optional(),
});
export function validateBody(schema) {
return (req, res, next) => {
const result = schema.safeParse(req.body);
if (!result.success) {
return res.status(400).json({ error: result.error.errors[0]?.message });
}
req.body = result.data; // Replace with parsed, coerced, trimmed data
next();
};
}
The key insight: by parsing req.body through a strict schema and replacing it with only the fields defined in the schema, any extra fields an attacker sends (like user_id: 99999 to try to hijack another user’s note) are silently stripped. I tested this — posting { title: “test”, user_id: 99999 } created a note owned by the authenticated user, not user 99999
File Upload Security (A04 — Insecure Design)
Trusting the Content-Type header a browser sends on an upload is a classic mistake. It’s trivially spoofable — rename evil.html to photo.jpg and the header will say image/jpeg . I check the actual file bytes:
function detectRealMimeType(buffer) {
// JPEG: starts with FF D8 FF
if (buffer[0] === 0xff && buffer[1] === 0xd8 && buffer[2] === 0xff) {
return 'image/jpeg';
}
// PNG: starts with 89 50 4E 47 0D 0A 1A 0A
if (
buffer[0] === 0x89 && buffer[1] === 0x50 && buffer[2] === 0x4e && buffer[3] === 0x47 &&
buffer[4] === 0x0d && buffer[5] === 0x0a && buffer[6] === 0x1a && buffer[7] === 0x0a
) {
return 'image/png';
}
// GIF: starts with GIF87a or GIF89a
if (
buffer[0] === 0x47 && buffer[1] === 0x49 && buffer[2] === 0x46 && buffer[3] === 0x38 &&
(buffer[4] === 0x37 || buffer[4] === 0x39) && buffer[5] === 0x61
) {
return 'image/gif';
}
// WebP: RIFF....WEBP
if (
buffer[0] === 0x52 && buffer[1] === 0x49 && buffer[2] === 0x46 && buffer[3] === 0x46 &&
buffer[8] === 0x57 && buffer[9] === 0x45 && buffer[10] === 0x42 && buffer[11] === 0x50
) {
return 'image/webp';
}
return null;
}I tested this with a text file renamed to .png with a spoofed Content-Type: image/png header — it correctly got rejected with 415 Unsupported Media Type .
Broken Object Level Authorization (API1)
Every single note and media operation checks ownership:
// Not just: SELECT * FROM notes WHERE id = $1
// Always: SELECT * FROM notes WHERE id = $1 AND user_id = $2const result = await pool.query(
'SELECT * FROM notes WHERE id = $1 AND user_id = $2',
[req.params.id, req.userId] // req.userId comes from verified JWT
);
if (!result.rows[0]) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Note not found' });
Returning 404 (not 403 ) for resources that belong to other users is intentional — it avoids confirming that the resource exists at all.
Part 4: Full-Text Search with Postgres
Most apps implement search with LIKE ‘%query%’ . This is slow, can’t rank results, and doesn’t understand language. Postgres has a built-in full-text search engine that’s genuinely good.
// Search with relevance ranking
const result = await pool.query(
`SELECT ${NOTE_COLUMNS}, ts_rank(n.search_vector, websearch_to_tsquery('english', $2)) AS rank
FROM notes n
WHERE n.user_id = $1
AND n.search_vector @@ websearch_to_tsquery('english', $2)
ORDER BY rank DESC, n.updated_at DESC`,
[req.userId, query]
);websearch_to_tsquery handles natural language: deploy -production finds notes about deployment that don’t mention production. “exact phrase” finds exact matches. And it handles stemming — searching “deploying” finds notes containing “deploy”
